class Solution {
  public:
    int minChar(string& s) {
        // Write your code here
        int size = s.size();
        string rev = s;
        reverse(rev.begin(), rev.end());
        
        s += '$';
        s += rev;
        
        int n = s.size();
        vector<int> lps(n, 0);
        
        int pre = 0, suf = 1;
        
        while(suf < s.size()) 
        {
            if (s[pre] == s[suf])
            {
                lps[suf] = pre + 1;
                suf++, pre++;
            }
            else
            {
                if (pre == 0)   
                suf++;
                else
                {
                    pre = lps[pre - 1];
                }
            }
        }
        
        return size - lps[n - 1];
    }
};




Algorithm:

Reverse the string:
  Create a reversed copy of the original string.
Concatenate strings:
  Append a special character (e.g., '$') to the original string.
  Concatenate the reversed string to the original string.
Compute the Longest Prefix Suffix (LPS) array:
  Initialize an LPS array to store the length of the longest proper prefix which is also a suffix for each prefix of the concatenated string.
  Use a two-pointer approach to calculate the LPS array efficiently.
  Calculate the minimum characters to be added:
  The length of the original string minus the last element of the LPS array gives the minimum number of characters to be added.
Core Concept:

  The core concept behind this approach is the Longest Prefix Suffix (LPS) array. This array helps us identify the longest common prefix and     suffix   of a given string. By constructing a new string by concatenating the original string, a special character, and its reverse, we can leverage   the LPS array to find the minimum number of characters needed to make the original string a palindrome.

Explanation:

Concatenation and LPS Array:

Concatenating the original string and its reverse creates a string where the palindrome can be found as a prefix or suffix.
The LPS array helps us identify the longest common prefix and suffix of this concatenated string.
Finding the Minimum Characters:

The last element of the LPS array represents the length of the longest proper prefix that is also a suffix of the concatenated string.
Subtracting this length from the original string's length gives the minimum number of characters needed to be added to make the string a palindrome.

  By using the LPS array and the properties of palindromic strings, this algorithm efficiently calculates the minimum number of characters required to make a string a palindrome.
